{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1096.erdos_1096 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1096.erdos_1096.","id":"vf_4aa4e928fbdb714a","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1096: declared status 'proved'. Formalized: yes. Let $1<q<1+\\epsilon$ and consider the set of numbers of the shape $\\sum_{i\\in S}q^i$ (for all finite $S$), ordered by size as $0=x_1<x_2<\\cdots$.\n\nIs it true that, provided $\\epsilon>0$ is sufficiently small, $x_{k+1}-x_k \\to 0$? Current best: In \\cite{EJK90} Erd\\H{o}, Jo\\'{o}, and Komornik prove that any Pisot-Vijayaraghavan number cannot have this property, and also prove that, for any $1<q\\leq 2$,  $x_{k+1}-x_k\\leq 1$ for all $k$. Bugeaud \\cite{Bu96} proved that $1<q\\leq 2$ is a Pisot-Vijayaraghavan number if and only if\\[\\liminf (x_{k+1}^m-x_k^m)>0\\]for all $m\\geq 1$, where $x_k^m$ is the set of those numbers which can be written as a finite sum $\\sum_{n\\geq 0}c_nq^n$ for some $c_n\\in \\{0,\\ldots,m\\}$ (so that the sequence in the question is $x_k^1$). Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_fcecc94ed7fbdf06","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1096.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_4aa4e928fbdb714a","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:1096","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_4aa4e928fbdb714a","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"vf_fcecc94ed7fbdf06","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem iden